abstract: The Central Intelligence Agency and the National Security Agency both recently overhauled their showcases of espionage.
snippet: The Central Intelligence Agency and the National Security Agency both recently overhauled their showcases of espionage.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Two of the United States’ intelligence agencies have completely renovated their museums of spycraft, displaying dramatic stories of notable U.S. spies and informants, as well as paraphernalia from intelligence work. But one of the museums will remain off limits to the public.

main: Two Renovated Museums Offer a Peek at Spy Secrets — at Least for Some
print_headline: 2 Museums With Spy Secrets,  But One’s for Some Eyes Only

abstract: The writer of “The Glass Castle” starts a new chapter with a rip-roaring novel set during Prohibition.
snippet: The writer of “The Glass Castle” starts a new chapter with a rip-roaring novel set during Prohibition.
lead_paragraph: ORANGE, Va. — Jeannette Walls could have had a life of leisure after the big success of her 2005 memoir, “The Glass Castle,” but she has too much energy for that. She walks fast and talks fast. Her laugh can be as loud as a gunshot.

main: The Many Lives of Jeannette Walls
print_headline: A Life of Sifting Through Facts and Fables

abstract: Dozens of missiles knocked out heat and electricity systems around the country including in Kyiv, where two-thirds of its residents had no heat or water.
snippet: Dozens of missiles knocked out heat and electricity systems around the country including in Kyiv, where two-thirds of its residents had no heat or water.
lead_paragraph: KYIV, Ukraine — In subfreezing weather, Russia launched dozens of missiles and drones at Ukrainian energy systems on Friday, pitching millions of civilians into the cold and dark in its deadly campaign to batter — and freeze — the populace into submission.

main: In Subfreezing Cold, Waves of Russian Missiles Batter Ukraine
print_headline: Russian Missiles Plunge Millions Into Frigid Dark

original: By Andrew E. Kramer and Marc Santora

abstract: Moscow on Thursday fired the largest number of the air-launched weapons used in a single wave since the war began a year ago.
snippet: Moscow on Thursday fired the largest number of the air-launched weapons used in a single wave since the war began a year ago.
lead_paragraph: Russia’s biggest aerial attack in weeks hit targets across Ukraine on Thursday, using a complex barrage of weapons. Ukraine’s Air Force said that among them were six of Russia’s air-launched hypersonic missiles, known as Kinzhals, or Daggers — the most used in a single wave since the war began a year ago.

main: Questions surround Russia’s use of hypersonic missiles in its latest attack.
print_headline: Missiles Used In Big Attack Are a Surprise

original: By John Ismay, Matthew Mpoke Bigg and Andrew E. Kramer

abstract: A twisty MGM+ series tells the story of Kim Philby, a British agent secretly working for the Soviet Union, and Nicholas Elliott, his closest friend.
snippet: A twisty MGM+ series tells the story of Kim Philby, a British agent secretly working for the Soviet Union, and Nicholas Elliott, his closest friend.
lead_paragraph: “Why wasn’t he in custody?” asks the MI5 officer Lily Thomas. It is January 1963, and Thomas is talking about Kim Philby, a British intelligence agent who, after being exposed as a Soviet spy, has escaped to Moscow. Nicholas Elliott, Philby’s closest friend and a fellow member of the foreign intelligence agency MI6, looks slightly nonplused. “Well, that’s not how we —” he begins, before coming to an abrupt halt.

main: In ‘A Spy Among Friends,’ B.F.F. Betrayal at an International Level
print_headline: A Betrayal Both Personal and International

abstract: The 2003 box office flop has been embraced by a younger generation that understands the role-playing nature of courtship.
snippet: The 2003 box office flop has been embraced by a younger generation that understands the role-playing nature of courtship.
lead_paragraph: Twenty years ago, before the retro-chic sex comedy “Down With Love” was released in American theaters, the anticipation was high. The Tribeca Film Festival, then in its second year, made the film its flashy opening-night selection. Cheeky promotional images of its two stars were ubiquitous: Renée Zellweger was a bona fide It Girl following the success of “Bridget Jones’s Diary” (2001) and “Chicago” (2002); and Ewan McGregor was riding high after the one-two punch of “Moulin Rouge” (2001) and “Star Wars: Episode II — Attack of the Clones” (2002).

main: ‘Down With Love’ 20 Years Later: Celebrating the Phoniness of Rom-Coms
